04678nam a22006735i 9781479876426DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798764267 a10.18574/97814798764262doi  a(DE-B1597)548367  a(OCoLC)923734910  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aML3917.U6bB97 2016 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a780.89680756762231 aByrd, Samuel K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Sounds of Latinidad :bImmigrants Making Music and Creating Culture in a Southern City /cSamuel K. Byrd. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSocial Transformations in American Anthropology ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Charlotte, a Globalizing City -- t2. The Latin Music Scene in Charlotte -- t3. Bands Making Musical Communities -- t4. "Thursday Is Bakalao's Day!" -- t5. The "Collective Circle" -- t6. Shifting Urban Genres -- t7. Race and the Expanding Borderlands Condition -- t8. The Festival -- t9. Musicians' Ethics and Aesthetics -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Sounds of Latinidad explores the Latino music scene as a lens through which to understand changing ideas about latinidad in the New South. Focusing on Latino immigrant musicians and their fans in Charlotte, North Carolina, the volume shows how limited economic mobility, social marginalization, and restrictive immigration policies have stymied immigrants' access to the American dream and musicians' dreams of success. Instead, Latin music has become a way to form community, debate political questions, and claim cultural citizenship. The volume illuminates the complexity of Latina/o musicians' lives. They find themselves at the intersection of culture and politics, often pushed to define a vision of what it means to be Latino in a globalizing city in the Nuevo South. At the same time, they often avoid overt political statements and do not participate in immigrants' rights struggles, instead holding a cautious view of political engagement. Yet despite this politics of ambivalence, Latina/o musicians do assert intellectual agency and engage in a politics that is embedded in their musical community, debating aesthetics, forging collective solidarity with their audiences, and protesting poor working conditions. Challenging scholarship on popular music that focuses on famous artists or on one particular genre, this volume demonstrates how exploring the everyday lives of ordinary musicians can lead to a deeper understanding of musicians' role in society. It argues that the often overlooked population of Latina/o musicians should be central to our understanding of what it means to live in a southern U.S. city today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aHispanic AmericanszNorth CarolinazCharlottevMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aLatin AmericanszNorth CarolinazCharlottexMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aMusicxSocial aspectszNorth CarolinazCharlotte. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479876426423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479876426.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  a